# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gorm-orm-go
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gorm-orm-go/active-record-pattern] In software engineering, the **active record pattern** is an architectural pattern.
[src:gorm-orm-go/active-record-pattern] It is found in software that stores in-memory object data in relational databases.
[src:gorm-orm-go/active-record-pattern] It was named by Martin Fowler in his 2003 book *Patterns of Enterprise Application Architecture*.
[src:gorm-orm-go/active-record-pattern] The interface of an object conforming to this pattern would include functions such as Insert, Update, and Delete, plus properties that correspond more or less directly to the columns in the underlying database table.
[src:gorm-orm-go/active-record-pattern] The Active Record pattern is a Data Access Layer that performs bidirectional transfer of data between a persistent data store (often a relational database) and an in-memory data representation (the domain layer).
[src:gorm-orm-go/active-record-pattern] A database table or view is wrapped into a class.
[src:gorm-orm-go/active-record-pattern] Thus, an object instance is tied to a single row in the table.
[src:gorm-orm-go/active-record-pattern] After creation of an object, a new row is added to the table upon save.
[src:gorm-orm-go/active-record-pattern] Any object loaded gets its information from the database.
[src:gorm-orm-go/active-record-pattern] When an object is updated, the corresponding row in the table is also updated.
[src:gorm-orm-go/active-record-pattern] The wrapper class implements accessor methods or properties for each column in the table or view.
[src:gorm-orm-go/active-record-pattern] This pattern is commonly used by object persistence tools and in object–relational mapping (ORM).
[src:gorm-orm-go/active-record-pattern] Typically, foreign key relationships will be exposed as an object instance of the appropriate type via a property.
[src:gorm-orm-go/active-record-pattern] Implementations of the concept can be found in various frameworks for many programming environments.
[src:gorm-orm-go/active-record-pattern] This will find a new `Part` object based on the first matching row from the `parts` table whose `name` column has the value "gearbox".
[src:gorm-orm-go/active-record-pattern] Various libraries implement an active record pattern framework, such as POCO C++ Libraries in library `Poco::ActiveRecord`.
[src:gorm-orm-go/active-record-pattern] This is a simple example of an active record object `User`, in Java.
[src:gorm-orm-go/active-record-pattern] Here the `User` class is both the model and data access object and provides `save()`, `find()`, and `delete()` methods.
[src:gorm-orm-go/active-record-pattern] Another critique of the active record pattern is that, due to the strong coupling of database interaction and application logic, an active record object does not follow the single responsibility principle and separation of concerns.
[src:gorm-orm-go/active-record-pattern] This is opposed to multitier architecture, which properly addresses these practices.
[src:gorm-orm-go/active-record-pattern] Because of this, the active record pattern is best and most often employed in simple applications that are all forms-over-data with CRUD functionality, or only as one part of an architecture.
[src:gorm-orm-go/active-record-pattern] Typically that part is data access and why several ORMs implement the active record pattern.
[src:gorm-orm-go/database-connection] A **database connection** is a facility in computer science that allows client software to talk to database server software, whether on the same machine or not.
[src:gorm-orm-go/database-connection] A **connection** is required to send commands and receive answers, usually in the form of a result set.
[src:gorm-orm-go/database-connection] Connections are a key concept in data-centric programming.
[src:gorm-orm-go/database-connection] Since some DBMS engines require considerable time to connect, connection pooling was invented to improve performance.
[src:gorm-orm-go/database-connection] No command can be performed against a database without an "open and available" connection to it.
[src:gorm-orm-go/database-connection] Connections are built by supplying an underlying driver or provider with a connection string, which is a way of addressing a specific database or server and instance as well as user authentication credentials (for example, ***Server=**sql_box;**Database=**Common;**User ID=**uid;**Pwd=**password;*).
[src:gorm-orm-go/database-connection] Once a connection has been built it can be opened and closed at will, and properties (such as the command time-out length, or transaction, if one exists) can be set.
[src:gorm-orm-go/database-connection] The Connection String is composed of a set of key/value pairs as dictated by the data access interface and data provider being used.
[src:gorm-orm-go/database-connection] Many databases (such as PostgreSQL) only allow one operation to be performed at a time on each connection.
[src:gorm-orm-go/database-connection] If a request for data (a SQL Select statement) is sent to the database and a result set is returned, the connection is open but not available for other operations until the client finishes consuming the result set.
[src:gorm-orm-go/database-connection] Other databases, like SQL Server 2005 (and later), do not impose this limitation.
[src:gorm-orm-go/database-connection] However, databases that provide multiple operations per connection usually incur far more overhead than those that permit only a single operation task at a time.
[src:gorm-orm-go/database-connection] Database connections are finite and expensive and can take a disproportionately long time to create relative to the operations performed on them.
[src:gorm-orm-go/database-connection] It is inefficient for an application to create, use, and close a database connection whenever it needs to update a database.
[src:gorm-orm-go/database-connection] Connection pooling is a technique designed to alleviate this problem.
[src:gorm-orm-go/database-connection] A pool of database connections can be created and then shared among the applications that need to access the database.
[src:gorm-orm-go/database-connection] The connection object obtained from the connection pool is often a wrapper around the actual database connection.
[src:gorm-orm-go/database-connection] The wrapper understands its relationship with the pool, and hides the details of the pool from the application.
[src:gorm-orm-go/database-connection] For example, the wrapper object can implement a "close" method that can be called just like the "close" method on the database connection.
[src:gorm-orm-go/database-connection] Unlike the method on the database connection, the method on the wrapper may not actually close the database connection, but instead return it to the pool.
[src:gorm-orm-go/database-connection] The application need not be aware of the connection pooling when it calls the methods on the wrapper object.
[src:gorm-orm-go/database-connection] This approach encourages the practice of opening a connection in an application only when needed, and closing it as soon as the work is done, rather than holding a connection open for the entire life of the application.
[src:gorm-orm-go/database-connection] In this manner, a relatively small number of connections can service a large number of requests.
[src:gorm-orm-go/database-connection] In a client/server architecture, on the other hand, a persistent connection is typically used so that server state can be managed.
[src:gorm-orm-go/database-connection] This "state" includes server-side cursors, temporary products, connection-specific functional settings, and so on.
[src:gorm-orm-go/database-connection] An application failure occurs when the connection pool overflows.
[src:gorm-orm-go/database-connection] This can occur if all of the connections in the pool are in use when an application requests a connection.
[src:gorm-orm-go/database-connection] For example, the application may use a connection for too long when too many clients attempt to access the web site or one or more operations are blocked or simply inefficient.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] A third-party source-to-source compiler, GopherJS, transpiles Go to JavaScript for front-end web development.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Go was designed at Google in 2007 to improve programming productivity in an era of multicore, networked machines and large codebases.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Its designers were primarily motivated by their shared dislike of C++.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Go was publicly announced in November 2009, and version 1.0 was released in March 2012.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Go is widely used in production at Google and in many other organizations and open-source projects.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] In retrospect the Go authors judged Go to be successful due to the overall engineering work around the language, including the runtime support for the language's concurrency feature.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] The gopher mascot was introduced in 2009 for the open source launch of the language.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Renée French, who had designed the rabbit mascot for Plan 9, adapted the gopher from an earlier WFMU T-shirt design.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] In November 2016, the Go and Go Mono fonts were released by type designers Charles Bigelow and Kris Holmes specifically for use by the Go project.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Go is a humanist sans-serif resembling Lucida Grande, and Go Mono is monospaced.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Both fonts adhere to the WGL4 character set and were designed to be legible with a large x-height and distinct letterforms.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Both Go and Go Mono adhere to the DIN 1450 standard by having a slashed zero, lowercase `i` with a tail, and an uppercase `I` with serifs.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] In April 2018, the original logo was redesigned by brand designer Adam Smith.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] The new logo is a modern, stylized GO slanting right with trailing streamlines.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] The lack of support for generic programming in initial versions of Go drew considerable criticism.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] The designers expressed an openness to generic programming and noted that built-in functions *were* in fact type-generic, but are treated as special cases; Pike called this a weakness that might be changed at some point.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] The Google team built at least one compiler for an experimental Go dialect with generics, but did not release it.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] In August 2018, the Go principal contributors published draft designs for generic programming and error handling and asked users to submit feedback.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] However, the error handling proposal was eventually abandoned.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] In June 2020, a new draft design document was published that would add the necessary syntax to Go for declaring generic functions and types.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] A code translation tool, *go2go*, was provided to allow users to try the new syntax, along with a generics-enabled version of the online Go Playground.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Generics were finally added to Go in version 1.18 on March 15, 2022.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Go 1 guarantees compatibility for the language specification and major parts of the standard library.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] All versions up through the current Go 1.26 release have maintained this promise.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Go uses a `go1.[major].[patch]` versioning format, such as `go1.26.0` and each major Go release is supported until there are two newer major releases.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Unlike most software, Go calls the second number in a version the major, i.e., in `go1.26.0` the `26` is the major version.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] This is because Go plans to never reach 2.0, prioritizing backwards compatibility over potential breaking changes.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Go is influenced by C (especially the Plan 9 dialect), but with an emphasis on greater simplicity and safety.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Go's syntax includes changes from C aimed at keeping code concise and readable.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] A combined declaration/initialization operator was introduced that allows the programmer to write `i := 3` or `s := "Hello, world!"`, without specifying the types of variables used.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] This contrasts with C's `int i = 3;` and `char *s = "Hello, world!";` (though since C23 type inference has been supported using `auto`, like C++).
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Go also removes the requirement to use parentheses in `if` statement conditions.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Semicolons still terminate statements; but are implicit when the end of a line occurs.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Methods may return multiple values, and returning a `result, err` pair is the conventional way a method indicates an error to its caller in Go.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Go adds literal syntaxes for initializing struct parameters by name and for initializing maps and slices.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] As an alternative to C's three-statement `for` loop, Go's `range` expressions allow concise iteration over arrays, slices, strings, maps, and channels.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Go has a number of built-in types, including numeric ones (`byte`, `int64`, `float32`, etc.), Booleans, and byte strings (`string`).
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Strings are immutable; built-in operators and keywords (rather than functions) provide concatenation, comparison, and UTF-8 encoding/decoding.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Record types can be defined with the `struct` keyword.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Note that `byte` is an alias for `uint8` and `rune` is an alias for `int32`.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] For each type `T` and each non-negative integer constant `n`, there is an array type denoted `[n]T`; arrays of differing lengths are thus of different types.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Dynamic arrays are available as "slices", denoted `[]T` for some type `T` (compare to other languages like C/C++ and Java, where instead the arrays are denoted `T[]`) These have a length and a *capacity* specifying when new memory needs to be allocated to expand the array.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Several slices may share their underlying memory.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] For a pair of types `K`, `V`, the type `map[K]V` is the type mapping type-`K` keys to type-`V` values, which can be thought of as equivalent to `Map<K, V>` in other languages.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] The Go Programming Language specification does not give any performance guarantees or implementation requirements for map types, though it is usually implemented as a hash table (equivalent to `HashMap<K, V>` in other languages).
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Hash tables are built into the language, with special syntax and built-in functions.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] `chan T` is a *channel* that allows sending values of type `T` between concurrent Go processes.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Aside from its support for interfaces, Go's type system is nominal: the `type` keyword can be used to define a new *named type*, which is distinct from other named types that have the same layout (in the case of a `struct`, the same members in the same order).
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Some conversions between types (e.g., between the various integer types) are pre-defined and adding a new type may define additional conversions, but conversions between named types must always be invoked explicitly.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] With this type definition, `ipv4addr(x)` interprets the `uint32` value `x` as an IP address.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Simply assigning `x` to a variable of type `ipv4addr` is a type error.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Any named type has a method set associated with it.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Due to nominal typing, this method definition adds a method to `ipv4addr`, but not on `uint32`.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] While methods have special definition and call syntax, there is no distinct method type.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Go provides two features that replace class inheritance.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] The first is *embedding*, which can be viewed as an automated form of composition.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] The second are its *interfaces*, which provides runtime polymorphism.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Interfaces are a class of types and provide a limited form of structural typing in the otherwise nominal type system of Go.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] An object which is of an interface type is also of another type, much like C++ objects being simultaneously of a base and derived class.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] The design of Go interfaces was inspired by protocols from the Smalltalk programming language.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Multiple sources use the term duck typing when describing Go interfaces.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Although the term duck typing is not precisely defined and therefore not wrong, it usually implies that type conformance is not statically checked.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Because conformance to a Go interface is checked statically by the Go compiler (except when performing a type assertion), the Go authors prefer the term *structural typing*.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] The definition of an interface type lists required methods by name and type.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Any object of type T for which functions exist matching all the required methods of interface type I is an object of type I as well.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] The definition of type T need not (and cannot) identify type I.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] then both a `Square` and a `Circle` are implicitly a `Shape` and can be assigned to a `Shape`-typed variable.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] In formal language, Go's interface system provides structural rather than nominal typing.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Interfaces can embed other interfaces with the effect of creating a combined interface that is satisfied by exactly the types that implement the embedded interface and any methods that the newly defined interface adds.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] The Go standard library uses interfaces to provide genericity in several places, including the input/output system that is based on the concepts of `Reader` and `Writer`.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Besides calling methods via interfaces, Go allows converting interface values to other types with a run-time type check.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] The *empty interface* `interface{}` is an important base case because it can refer to an item of *any* concrete type.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] It is similar to the `Object` class in Java or C# or `void*` in C or `Any` in C++ and Rust and is satisfied by any type, including built-in types like `int`.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Code using the empty interface cannot simply call methods (or built-in operators) on the referred-to object, but it can store the `interface{}` value, try to convert it to a more useful type via a type assertion or type switch, or inspect it with Go's `reflect` package.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Because `interface{}` can refer to any value, it is a limited way to escape the restrictions of static typing, like `void*` in C but with additional run-time type checks.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] The `interface{}` type can be used to model structured data of any arbitrary schema in Go, such as JSON or YAML data, by representing it as a `map[string]interface{}` (map of string to empty interface).
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] This recursively describes data in the form of a dictionary with string keys and values of any type.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Interface values are implemented using pointer to data and a second pointer to run-time type information.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Like some other types implemented using pointers in Go, interface values are `nil` if uninitialized.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Since version 1.18, Go supports generic code using parameterized types.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Functions and types now have the ability to be generic using type parameters.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] These type parameters are specified within square brackets, right after the function or type name.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] The compiler transforms the generic function or type into non-generic by substituting *type arguments* for the type parameters provided, either explicitly by the user or type inference by the compiler.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] This transformation process is referred to as type instantiation.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Interfaces now can define a set of types (known as type set) using `|` (Union) operator, as well as a set of methods.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] These changes were made to support type constraints in generics code.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] For a generic function or type, a constraint can be thought of as the type of the type argument: a meta-type.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] This new `~T` syntax will be the first use of `~` as a token in Go.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] `~T` means the set of all types whose underlying type is `T`.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Go uses the `iota` identifier to create enumerated constants.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] In Go's package system, each package has a path (e.g., `"compress/bzip2"` or `"golang.org/x/net/html"`) and a name (e.g., `bzip2` or `html`).
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] By default other packages' definitions must *always* be prefixed with the other package's name.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] However the name used can be changed from the package name, and if imported as `_`, then no package prefix is required.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Only the *capitalized* names from other packages are accessible: `io.Reader` is public but `bzip2.reader` is not.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] The Go language has built-in facilities, as well as library support, for writing concurrent programs.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] The runtime is asynchronous: program execution that performs, for example, a network read will be suspended until data is available to process, allowing other parts of the program to perform other work.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] This is built into the runtime and does not require any changes in program code.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] The go runtime also automatically schedules concurrent operations (goroutines) across multiple CPUs; this can achieve parallelism for a properly written program.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] The primary concurrency construct is the *goroutine*, a type of green thread.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] A function call prefixed with the `go` keyword starts a function in a new goroutine.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] While a standard library package featuring most of the classical concurrency control structures (mutex locks, etc.) is available, idiomatic concurrent programs instead prefer *channels*, which send messages between goroutines.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Optional buffers store messages in FIFO order and allow sending goroutines to proceed before their messages are received.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Channels are typed, so that a channel of type `chan T` can only be used to transfer messages of type `T`.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Special syntax is used to operate on them; `<-ch` is an expression that causes the executing goroutine to block until a value comes in over the channel `ch`, while `ch <- x` sends the value `x` (possibly blocking until another goroutine receives the value).
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] The built-in `switch`-like `select` statement can be used to implement non-blocking communication on multiple channels; see below for an example.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Go has a memory model describing how goroutines must use channels or other operations to safely share data.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] The existence of channels does not by itself set Go apart from actor model-style concurrent languages like Erlang, where messages are addressed directly to actors (corresponding to goroutines).
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] In the actor model, channels are themselves actors, therefore addressing a channel just means to address an actor.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] The actor style can be simulated in Go by maintaining a one-to-one correspondence between goroutines and channels, but the language allows multiple goroutines to share a channel or a single goroutine to send and receive on multiple channels.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] From these tools one can build concurrent constructs like worker pools, pipelines (in which, say, a file is decompressed and parsed as it downloads), background calls with timeout, "fan-out" parallel calls to a set of services, and others.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Channels have also found uses further from the usual notion of interprocess communication, like serving as a concurrency-safe list of recycled buffers, implementing coroutines (which helped inspire the name *goroutine*), and implementing iterators.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Concurrency-related structural conventions of Go (channels and alternative channel inputs) are derived from Tony Hoare's communicating sequential processes model.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Unlike previous concurrent programming languages such as Occam or Limbo (a language on which Go co-designer Rob Pike worked), Go does not provide any built-in notion of safe or verifiable concurrency.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] While the communicating-processes model is favored in Go, it is not the only one: all goroutines in a program share a single address space.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] This means that mutable objects and pointers can be shared between goroutines; see § Lack of data race safety, below.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Although Go's concurrency features are not aimed primarily at parallel processing, they can be used to program shared-memory multi-processor machines.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Various studies have been done into the effectiveness of this approach.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] One of these studies compared the size (in lines of code) and speed of programs written by a seasoned programmer not familiar with the language and corrections to these programs by a Go expert (from Google's development team), doing the same for Chapel, Cilk and Intel TBB.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] The study found that the non-expert tended to write divide-and-conquer algorithms with one `go` statement per recursion, while the expert wrote distribute-work-synchronize programs using one goroutine per processor core.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] The expert's programs were usually faster, but also longer.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Go's approach to concurrency can be summarized as "don't communicate by sharing memory; share memory by communicating".
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] There are no restrictions on how goroutines access shared data, making data races possible.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Specifically, unless a program explicitly synchronizes via channels or other means, writes from one goroutine might be partly, entirely, or not at all visible to another, often with no guarantees about ordering of writes.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Furthermore, Go's *internal data structures* like interface values, slice headers, hash tables, and string headers are not immune to data races, so type and memory safety can be violated in multithreaded programs that modify shared instances of those types without synchronization.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Instead of language support, safe concurrent programming thus relies on conventions; for example, Chisnall recommends an idiom called "aliases xor mutable", meaning that passing a mutable value (or pointer) over a channel signals a transfer of ownership over the value to its receiver.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] The gc toolchain has an optional data race detector that can check for unsynchronized access to shared memory during runtime since version 1.1, additionally a best-effort race detector is also included by default since version 1.6 of the gc runtime for access to the `map` data type.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] The linker in the gc toolchain creates statically linked binaries by default; therefore all Go binaries include the Go runtime.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Go deliberately omits certain features common in other languages, including (implementation) inheritance, assertions, pointer arithmetic, implicit type conversions, untagged unions, and tagged unions.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] The designers added only those facilities that all three agreed on.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Of the omitted language features, the designers explicitly argue against assertions and pointer arithmetic, while defending the choice to omit type inheritance as giving a more useful language, encouraging instead the use of interfaces to achieve dynamic dispatch and composition to reuse code.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Exception handling was initially omitted in Go due to lack of a "design that gives value proportionate to the complexity".
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] An exception-like `panic`/`recover` mechanism that avoids the usual `try-catch` control structure was proposed and released in the March 30, 2010 snapshot.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] The Go authors advise using it for unrecoverable errors such as those that should halt an entire program or server request, or as a shortcut to propagate errors up the stack within a package.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Across package boundaries, Go includes a canonical error type, and multi-value returns using this type are the standard idiom.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] It also includes profiling and debugging support, fuzzing capabilities to detect bugs, runtime instrumentation (for example, to track garbage collection pauses), and a data race detector.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Another tool maintained by the Go team but is not included in Go distributions is `gopls`, a language server that provides IDE features such as intelligent code completion to Language Server Protocol compatible editors.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] An ecosystem of third-party tools adds to the standard distribution, such as `gocode`, which enables code autocompletion in many text editors, `goimports`, which automatically adds/removes package imports as needed, and `errcheck`, which detects code that might unintentionally ignore errors.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] where "fmt" is the package for *formatted I/O*, similar to C's <stdio.h> or C++ <print>.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] The following simple program demonstrates Go's concurrency features to implement an asynchronous program.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] It launches two lightweight threads ("goroutines"): one waits for the user to type some text, while the other implements a timeout.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] The select statement waits for either of these goroutines to send a message to the main routine, and acts on the first message to arrive (example adapted from David Chisnall's book).
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] The testing package provides support for automated testing of go packages.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] It is possible to run tests in parallel.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] The net/http package provides support for creating web applications.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] This example would show "Hello world!" when localhost:8080 is visited.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Go has found widespread adoption in various domains due to its robust standard library and ease of use.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] The interface system, and the deliberate omission of inheritance, were praised by Michele Simionato, who likened these characteristics to those of Standard ML, calling it "a shame that no popular language has followed [this] particular route".
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] By June 2015, its ranking had dropped to below 50th in the index, placing it lower than COBOL and Fortran.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] But as of January 2017, its ranking had surged to 13th, indicating significant growth in popularity and adoption.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] Go was again awarded TIOBE Programming Language of the Year in 2016.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] The evaluation got a rebuttal from the Go development team.
[src:gorm-orm-go/go-programming-language] On November 10, 2009, the day of the general release of the language, Francis McCabe, developer of the Go! programming language (note the exclamation point), requested a name change of Google's language to prevent confusion with his language, which he had spent 10 years developing.
[src:gorm-orm-go/object-relational-mapping] In object-oriented programming, data-management tasks act on objects that combine scalar values into objects.
[src:gorm-orm-go/object-relational-mapping] For example, consider an address book entry that represents a single person along with zero or more phone numbers and zero or more addresses.
[src:gorm-orm-go/object-relational-mapping] This could be modeled in an object-oriented implementation by a "Person object" with an attribute/field to hold each data item that the entry comprises: the person's name, a list of phone numbers, and a list of addresses.
[src:gorm-orm-go/object-relational-mapping] The list of phone numbers would itself contain "PhoneNumber objects" and so on.
[src:gorm-orm-go/object-relational-mapping] Each such address-book entry is treated as a single object by the programming language (it can be referenced by a single variable containing a pointer to the object, for instance).
[src:gorm-orm-go/object-relational-mapping] Various methods can be associated with the object, such as methods to return the preferred phone number, the home address, and so on.
[src:gorm-orm-go/object-relational-mapping] By contrast, relational databases, such as SQL, group scalars into tuples, which are then enumerated in tables.
[src:gorm-orm-go/object-relational-mapping] Tuples and objects have some general similarity, in that they are both ways to collect values into named fields such that the whole collection can be manipulated as a single compound entity.
[src:gorm-orm-go/object-relational-mapping] They have many differences, though, in particular: lifecycle management (row insertion and deletion, versus garbage collection or reference counting), references to other entities (object references, versus foreign key references), and inheritance (non-existent in relational databases).
[src:gorm-orm-go/object-relational-mapping] As well, objects are managed on-heap and are under full control of a single process, while database tuples are shared and must incorporate locking, merging, and retry.
[src:gorm-orm-go/object-relational-mapping] Object–relational mapping provides automated support for mapping tuples to objects and back, while accounting for all of these differences.
[src:gorm-orm-go/object-relational-mapping] The heart of the problem involves translating the logical representation of the objects into an atomized form that is capable of being stored in the database while preserving the properties of the objects and their relationships so that they can be reloaded as objects when needed.
[src:gorm-orm-go/object-relational-mapping] If this storage and retrieval functionality is implemented, the objects are said to be persistent.
[src:gorm-orm-go/object-relational-mapping] Implementation-specific details of storage drivers are generally wrapped in an API in the programming language in use, exposing methods to interact with the storage medium in a way which is simpler and more in line with the paradigms of surrounding code.
[src:gorm-orm-go/object-relational-mapping] The following is a simple example, written in C# code, to execute a query written in SQL using a database engine.
[src:gorm-orm-go/object-relational-mapping] In contrast, the following makes use of an ORM-job API which makes it possible to write code that naturally makes use of the features of the language.
[src:gorm-orm-go/object-relational-mapping] The case above makes use of an object representing the storage repository and methods of that object.
[src:gorm-orm-go/object-relational-mapping] Other frameworks might provide code as static methods, as in the example below, and yet other methods may not implement an object-oriented system at all.
[src:gorm-orm-go/object-relational-mapping] Often the choice of paradigm is made for the best fit of the ORM into the surrounding language's design principles.
[src:gorm-orm-go/object-relational-mapping] Compared to traditional techniques of exchange between an object-oriented language and a relational database, ORM often reduces the amount of code that needs to be written.
[src:gorm-orm-go/object-relational-mapping] Disadvantages of ORM tools generally stem from the high level of abstraction obscuring what is actually happening in the implementation code.
[src:gorm-orm-go/object-relational-mapping] Another approach is to use an object-oriented database management system (OODBMS) or document-oriented databases such as native XML databases that provide more flexibility in data modeling.
[src:gorm-orm-go/object-relational-mapping] OODBMSs are databases designed specifically for working with object-oriented values.
[src:gorm-orm-go/object-relational-mapping] Using an OODBMS eliminates the need for converting data to and from its SQL form, as the data is stored in its original object representation and relationships are directly represented, rather than requiring join tables/operations.
[src:gorm-orm-go/object-relational-mapping] The equivalent of ORMs for document-oriented databases are called object-document mappers (ODMs).
[src:gorm-orm-go/object-relational-mapping] Document-oriented databases also prevent the user from having to "shred" objects into table rows.
[src:gorm-orm-go/object-relational-mapping] Many of these systems also support the XQuery query language to retrieve datasets.
[src:gorm-orm-go/object-relational-mapping] Object-oriented databases tend to be used in complex, niche applications.
[src:gorm-orm-go/object-relational-mapping] One of the arguments against using an OODBMS is that it may not be able to execute ad-hoc, application-independent queries.
[src:gorm-orm-go/object-relational-mapping] For this reason, many programmers find themselves more at home with an object-SQL mapping system, even though most object-oriented databases are able to process SQL queries to a limited extent.
[src:gorm-orm-go/object-relational-mapping] Other OODBMS provide replication to SQL databases, as a means of addressing the need for ad-hoc queries, while preserving well-known query patterns.
[src:gorm-orm-go/object-relational-mapping] A variety of difficulties arise when considering how to match an object system to a relational database.
[src:gorm-orm-go/object-relational-mapping] These difficulties are referred to as the object–relational impedance mismatch.
[src:gorm-orm-go/object-relational-mapping] An alternative to implementing ORM is use of the native procedural languages provided with every major database.
[src:gorm-orm-go/object-relational-mapping] These can be called from the client using SQL statements.
[src:gorm-orm-go/object-relational-mapping] The Data Access Object (DAO) design pattern is used to abstract these statements and offer a lightweight object-oriented interface to the rest of the application.
[src:gorm-orm-go/object-relational-mapping] ORMs are limited to their predefined functionality, which may not cover all edge cases or database features.
[src:gorm-orm-go/object-relational-mapping] They usually mitigate this limitation by providing users with an interface to write raw queries, such as Django ORM.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] A **relational database** (**RDB**) is a database based on the relational model of data, as proposed by E.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] A Relational Database Management System (RDBMS) is a type of database management system that stores data in a structured format using rows and columns.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Many relational database systems are equipped with the option of using SQL (Structured Query Language) for querying and updating the database.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] The concept of relational database was defined by E.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Codd introduced the term *relational* in his research paper "A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks".
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] In this paper and later papers, he defined what he meant by *relation*.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] One well-known definition of what constitutes a relational database system is composed of Codd's 12 rules.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Provide relational operators to manipulate the data in tabular form.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] In 1974, IBM began developing System R, a research project to develop a prototype RDBMS.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] The first system sold as an RDBMS was Multics Relational Data Store (June 1976).
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Oracle was released in 1979 by Relational Software, now Oracle Corporation.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Other examples of an RDBMS include IBM Db2, SAP Sybase ASE, and Informix.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] In 1984, the first RDBMS for Macintosh began being developed, code-named Silver Surfer, and was released in 1987 as 4th Dimension and known today as 4D.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] The most common definition of an RDBMS is a product that presents a view of data as a collection of rows and columns, even if it is not based strictly upon relational theory.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] By this definition, RDBMS products typically implement some but not all of Codd's 12 rules.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] A second school of thought argues that if a database does not implement all of Codd's rules (or the current understanding on the relational model, as expressed by Christopher J.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Date, Hugh Darwen and others), it is not relational.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] This view, shared by many theorists and other strict adherents to Codd's principles, would disqualify most DBMSs as not relational.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] For clarification, they often refer to some RDBMSs as *truly-relational database management systems* (TRDBMS), naming others *pseudo-relational database management systems* (PRDBMS).
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] As of 2009, most commercial relational DBMSs employ SQL as their query language.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Alternative query languages have been proposed and implemented, notably the pre-1996 implementation of Ingres QUEL.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] A relational model organizes data into one or more tables (or "relations") of columns and rows, with a unique key identifying each row.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Generally, each table/relation represents one "entity type" (such as customer or product).
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] The rows represent instances of that type of entity (such as "Lee" or "chair") and the columns represent values attributed to that instance (such as address or price).
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Each row in a table has its own unique key.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Rows in a table can be linked to rows in other tables by adding a column for the unique key of the linked row (such columns are known as foreign keys).
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Codd showed that data relationships of arbitrary complexity can be represented by a simple set of concepts.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Part of this processing involves consistently being able to select or modify one and only one row in a table.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Therefore, most physical implementations have a unique primary key (PK) for each row in a table.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] When a new row is written to the table, a new unique value for the primary key is generated; this is the key that the system uses primarily for accessing the table.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] System performance is optimized for PKs.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Other, more natural keys may also be identified and defined as alternate keys (AK).
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Often several columns are needed to form an AK (this is one reason why a single integer column is usually made the PK).
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Both PKs and AKs have the ability to uniquely identify a row within a table.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Additional technology may be applied to ensure a unique ID across the world, a globally unique identifier, when there are broader system requirements.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] The primary keys within a database are used to define the relationships among the tables.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] When a PK migrates to another table, it becomes a foreign key (FK) in the other table.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] When each cell can contain only one value and the PK migrates into a regular entity table, this design pattern can represent either a one-to-one or one-to-many relationship.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Most relational database designs resolve many-to-many relationships by creating an additional table that contains the PKs from both of the other entity tables – the relationship becomes an entity; the resolution table is then named appropriately and the two FKs are combined to form a PK.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] The migration of PKs to other tables is the second major reason why system-assigned integers are used normally as PKs; there is usually neither efficiency nor clarity in migrating a bunch of other types of columns.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Relationships are a logical connection between different tables (entities), established on the basis of interaction among these tables.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] These relationships can be modelled as an entity-relationship model.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] In order for a database management system (DBMS) to operate efficiently and accurately, it must use ACID transactions.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Part of the programming within an RDBMS is accomplished using stored procedures (SPs).
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Often procedures can be used to greatly reduce the amount of information transferred within and outside of a system.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] For increased security, the system design may grant access to only the stored procedures and not directly to the tables.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Fundamental stored procedures contain the logic needed to insert new and update existing data.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] More complex procedures may be written to implement additional rules and logic related to processing or selecting the data.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] The relational database was first defined in June 1970 by Edgar Codd, of IBM's San Jose Research Laboratory.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Codd's view of what qualifies as an RDBMS is summarized in Codd's 12 rules.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] A relational database has become the predominant type of database.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Other models besides the *relational model* include the hierarchical database model and the network model.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] In a relational database, a *relation* is a set of tuples that have the same attributes.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] A tuple usually represents an object and information about that object.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Objects are typically physical objects or concepts.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] A relation is usually described as a table, which is organized into rows and columns.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] All the data referenced by an attribute are in the same domain and conform to the same constraints.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] The relational model specifies that the tuples of a relation have no specific order and that the tuples, in turn, impose no order on the attributes.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Applications access data by specifying queries, which use operations such as *select* to identify tuples, *project* to identify attributes, and *join* to combine relations.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Relations can be modified using the *insert*, *delete*, and *update* operators.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] New tuples can supply explicit values or be derived from a query.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Similarly, queries identify tuples for updating or deleting.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] If the tuple contains a candidate or primary key then obviously it is unique; however, a primary key need not be defined for a row or record to be a tuple.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] The definition of a tuple requires that it be unique, but does not require a primary key to be defined.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Because a tuple is unique, its attributes by definition constitute a superkey.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] All data are stored and accessed via relations.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Relations that store data are called "base relations", and in implementations are called "tables".
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Other relations do not store data, but are computed by applying relational operations to other relations.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] These relations are sometimes called "derived relations".
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] In implementations these are called "views" or "queries".
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Derived relations are convenient in that they act as a single relation, even though they may grab information from several relations.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Also, derived relations can be used as an abstraction layer.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] A domain describes the set of possible values for a given attribute, and can be considered a constraint on the value of the attribute.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Mathematically, attaching a domain to an attribute means that any value for the attribute must be an element of the specified set.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] The character string *"ABC"*, for instance, is not in the integer domain, but the integer value *123* is.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Another example of domain describes the possible values for the field "CoinFace" as ("Heads","Tails").
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] So, the field "CoinFace" will not accept input values like (0,1) or (H,T).
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Constraints are often used to make it possible to further restrict the domain of an attribute.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] For instance, a constraint can restrict a given integer attribute to values between 1 and 10.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Constraints provide one method of implementing business rules in the database and support subsequent data use within the application layer.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] SQL implements constraint functionality in the form of check constraints.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Constraints restrict the data that can be stored in relations.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] These are usually defined using expressions that result in a Boolean value, indicating whether or not the data satisfies the constraint.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Constraints can apply to single attributes, to a tuple (restricting combinations of attributes) or to an entire relation.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Since every attribute has an associated domain, there are constraints (**domain constraints**).
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] The two principal rules for the relational model are known as **entity integrity** and **referential integrity**.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Every relation/table has a primary key, this being a consequence of a relation being a set.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] A primary key uniquely specifies a tuple within a table.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] While natural attributes (attributes used to describe the data being entered) are sometimes good primary keys, surrogate keys are often used instead.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] A surrogate key is an artificial attribute assigned to an object which uniquely identifies it (for instance, in a table of information about students at a school they might all be assigned a student ID in order to differentiate them).
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] The surrogate key has no intrinsic (inherent) meaning, but rather is useful through its ability to uniquely identify a tuple.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Another common occurrence, especially in regard to N:M cardinality is the composite key.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] A composite key is a key made up of two or more attributes within a table that (together) uniquely identify a record.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Foreign key refers to a field in a relational table that matches the primary key column of another table.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Foreign keys need not have unique values in the referencing relation.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] A foreign key can be used to cross-reference tables, and it effectively uses the values of attributes in the referenced relation to restrict the domain of one or more attributes in the referencing relation.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] A stored procedure is executable code that is associated with, and generally stored in, the database.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Stored procedures usually collect and customize common operations, like inserting a tuple into a relation, gathering statistical information about usage patterns, or encapsulating complex business logic and calculations.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Frequently they are used as an application programming interface (API) for security or simplicity.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Implementations of stored procedures on SQL RDBMS's often allow developers to take advantage of procedural extensions (often vendor-specific) to the standard declarative SQL syntax.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Stored procedures are not part of the relational database model, but all commercial implementations include them.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] An index is one way of providing quicker access to data.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Indices can be created on any combination of attributes on a relation.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Queries that filter using those attributes can find matching tuples directly using the index (similar to Hash table lookup), without having to check each tuple in turn.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] This is analogous to using the index of a book to go directly to the page on which the information you are looking for is found, so that you do not have to read the entire book to find what you are looking for.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Relational databases typically supply multiple indexing techniques, each of which is optimal for some combination of data distribution, relation size, and typical access pattern.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Indices are usually implemented via B+ trees, R-trees, and bitmaps.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Indices are usually not considered part of the database, as they are considered an implementation detail, though indices are usually maintained by the same group that maintains the other parts of the database.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] The use of efficient indexes on both primary and foreign keys can dramatically improve query performance.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] This is because B-tree indexes result in query times proportional to log(n) where n is the number of rows in a table and hash indexes result in constant time queries (no size dependency as long as the relevant part of the index fits into memory).
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Queries made against the relational database, and the derived relvars in the database are expressed in a relational calculus or a relational algebra.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] In his original relational algebra, Codd introduced eight relational operators in two groups of four operators each.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Other operators have been introduced or proposed since Codd's introduction of the original eight including relational comparison operators and extensions that offer support for nesting and hierarchical data, among others.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Normalization was first proposed by Codd as an integral part of the relational model.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] It encompasses a set of procedures designed to eliminate non-simple domains (non-atomic values) and the redundancy (duplication) of data, which in turn prevents data manipulation anomalies and loss of data integrity.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] The most common forms of normalization applied to databases are called the normal forms.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Connolly and Begg define database management system (DBMS) as a "software system that enables users to define, create, maintain and control access to the database".
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] RDBMS is an extension of that initialism that is sometimes used when the underlying database is relational.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] An alternative definition for a **relational database management system** is a database management system (DBMS) based on the relational model.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Most databases in widespread use today are based on this model.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] RDBMSs have been a common option for the storage of information in databases used for financial records, manufacturing and logistical information, personnel data, and other applications since the 1980s.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Relational databases have often replaced legacy hierarchical databases and network databases, because RDBMS were easier to implement and administer.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] However, due to the expanse of technologies, such as horizontal scaling of computer clusters, NoSQL databases have recently become popular as an alternative to RDBMS databases.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] Distributed Relational Database Architecture (DRDA) was designed by a workgroup within IBM in the period 1988 to 1994.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] DRDA enables network connected relational databases to cooperate to fulfill SQL requests.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] The messages, protocols, and structural components of DRDA are defined by the Distributed Data Management Architecture.
[src:gorm-orm-go/relational-database] According to research company Gartner, in 2011, the five leading proprietary software relational database vendors by revenue were Oracle (48.8%), IBM (20.2%), Microsoft (17.0%), SAP including Sybase (4.6%), and Teradata (3.7%).
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] Introduced in the 1970s, SQL offered two main advantages over older read–write APIs such as ISAM or VSAM.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] Firstly, it introduced the concept of accessing many records with one single command.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] Secondly, it eliminates the need to specify *how* to reach a record, i.e., with or without an index.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] Originally based upon relational algebra and tuple relational calculus, SQL consists of many types of statements, which may be informally classed as sublanguages, commonly: data query language (DQL), data definition language (DDL), data control language (DCL), and data manipulation language (DML).
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] The scope of SQL includes data query, data manipulation (insert, update, and delete), data definition (schema creation and modification), and data access control.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] Although SQL is essentially a declarative language (4GL), it also includes procedural elements.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] SQL was one of the first commercial languages to use Edgar F.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] The model was described in his influential 1970 paper, "A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks".
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] Despite not entirely adhering to the relational model as described by Codd, SQL became the most widely used database language.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] SQL became a standard of the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) in 1986 and of the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) in 1987.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] Since then, the standard has been revised multiple times to include a larger set of features and incorporate common extensions.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] Despite the existence of standards, virtually no implementations in existence adhere to it fully, and most SQL code requires at least some changes before being ported to different database systems.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] SQL was initially developed at IBM by Donald D.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] Boyce after learning about the relational model from Edgar F.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] This version, initially called SEQUEL (Structured English Query Language), was designed to manipulate and retrieve data stored in IBM's original quasirelational database management system, System R, which a group at IBM San Jose Research Laboratory had developed during the 1970s.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] Chamberlin and Boyce's first attempt at a relational database language was SQUARE (Specifying Queries in A Relational Environment), but it was difficult to use due to subscript/superscript notation.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] After moving to the San Jose Research Laboratory in 1973, they began work on a sequel to SQUARE.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] The original name SEQUEL, which is widely regarded as a pun on QUEL, the query language of Ingres, was later changed to SQL (dropping the vowels) because "SEQUEL" was a trademark of the UK-based Hawker Siddeley Dynamics Engineering Limited company.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] The label SQL later became the acronym for Structured Query Language.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] After testing SQL at customer test sites to determine the usefulness and practicality of the system, IBM began developing commercial products based on their System R prototype, including System/38, SQL/DS, and IBM Db2, which were commercially available in 1979, 1981, and 1983, respectively.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] IBM's endorsement caused the industry to move to SQL from alternatives like QUEL.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] In the late 1970s, Relational Software, Inc.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] (now Oracle Corporation) saw the potential of the concepts described by Codd, Chamberlin, and Boyce, and developed their own SQL-based RDBMS with aspirations of selling it to the U.S.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] Navy, Central Intelligence Agency, and other U.S. government agencies.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] In June 1979, Relational Software introduced one of the first commercially available implementations of SQL, Oracle V2 (Version2) for VAX computers.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] By 1986, ANSI and ISO standard groups officially adopted the standard "Database Language SQL" language definition.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] SQL implementations are incompatible between vendors and do not necessarily completely follow standards.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] In particular, date and time syntax, string concatenation, `NULL`s, and comparison case sensitivity vary from vendor to vendor.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] PostgreSQL and Mimer SQL strive for standards compliance, though PostgreSQL does not adhere to the standard in all cases.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] For example, the folding of unquoted names to lower case in PostgreSQL is incompatible with the SQL standard, which says that unquoted names should be folded to upper case.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] Thus, according to the standard, `Foo` should be equivalent to `FOO`, not `foo`.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] Popular implementations of SQL commonly omit support for basic features of Standard SQL, such as the `DATE` or `TIME` data types.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] The most obvious such examples, and incidentally the most popular commercial and proprietary SQL DBMSs, are Oracle (whose `DATE` behaves as `DATETIME`, and lacks a `TIME` type) and MS SQL Server (before the 2008 version).
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] As a result, SQL code can rarely be ported between database systems without modifications.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] SQL was adopted as a standard by the ANSI in 1986 as SQL-86 and the ISO in 1987.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] It is maintained by *ISO/IEC JTC 1, Information technology, Subcommittee SC 32, Data management and interchange*.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] Until 1996, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) data-management standards program certified SQL DBMS compliance with the SQL standard.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] Vendors now self-certify the compliance of their products.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] The original standard declared that the official pronunciation for "SQL" was an initialism: /ˌɛsˌkjuːˈɛl/ ("ess cue el").
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] Regardless, many English-speaking database professionals (including Donald Chamberlin himself) use the acronym-like pronunciation of /ˈsiːkwəl/ ("sequel"), mirroring the language's prerelease development name, "SEQUEL".
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] The standard is commonly denoted by the pattern: *ISO/IEC 9075-n:yyyy Part n: title*, or, as a shortcut, *ISO/IEC 9075*.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] Interested parties may purchase the standards documents from ISO, IEC, or ANSI.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] SQL is designed for a specific purpose: to query data contained in a relational database.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] SQL is a set-based, declarative programming language, not an imperative programming language like C or BASIC.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] However, extensions to Standard SQL add procedural programming language functionality, such as control-of-flow constructs.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] In addition to the standard SQL/PSM extensions and proprietary SQL extensions, procedural and object-oriented programmability is available on many SQL platforms via DBMS integration with other languages.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] The SQL standard defines SQL/JRT extensions (SQL Routines and Types for the Java Programming Language) to support Java code in SQL databases.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] Microsoft SQL Server 2005 uses the SQLCLR (SQL Server Common Language Runtime) to host managed .NET assemblies in the database, while prior versions of SQL Server were restricted to unmanaged extended stored procedures primarily written in C.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] PostgreSQL lets users write functions in a wide variety of languages—including Perl, Python, Tcl, JavaScript (PL/V8) and C.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] A distinction should be made between alternatives to SQL as a language, and alternatives to the relational model itself.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] Below are proposed relational alternatives to the SQL language.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] See navigational database and NoSQL for alternatives to the relational model.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] Distributed Relational Database Architecture (DRDA) was designed by a workgroup within IBM from 1988 to 1994.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] DRDA enables network-connected relational databases to cooperate to fulfill SQL requests.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] An interactive user or program can issue SQL statements to a local RDB and receive tables of data and status indicators in reply from remote RDBs.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] SQL statements can also be compiled and stored in remote RDBs as packages and then invoked by package name.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] This is important for the efficient operation of application programs that issue complex, high-frequency queries.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] It is especially important when the tables to be accessed are located in remote systems.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] Distributed SQL processing ala DRDA is distinctive from contemporary distributed SQL databases.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] SQL deviates in several ways from its theoretical foundation, the relational model and its tuple calculus.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] In that model, a table is a set of tuples, while in SQL, tables and query results are lists of rows; the same row may occur multiple times, and the order of rows can be employed in queries (e.g., in the `LIMIT` clause).
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] Critics argue that SQL should be replaced with a language that returns strictly to the original foundation: for example, see *The Third Manifesto* by Hugh Darwen and C.J.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] Early specifications did not support major features, such as primary keys.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] Result sets could not be named, and subqueries had not been defined.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] The lack of sum types has been described as a roadblock to full use of SQL's user-defined types.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] JSON support, for example, needed to be added by a new standard in 2016.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] The concept of Null is the subject of some debate.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] The Null marker indicates the absence of a value, and is distinct from a value of 0 for an integer column or an empty string for a text column.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] The concept of Nulls enforces the 3-valued-logic in SQL, which is a concrete implementation of the general 3-valued logic.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] Another popular criticism is that it allows duplicate rows, making integration with languages such as Python, whose data types might make accurately representing the data difficult, in terms of parsing and by the absence of modularity.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] This is usually avoided by declaring a primary key, or a unique constraint, with one or more columns that uniquely identify a row in the table.
[src:gorm-orm-go/sql] In a sense similar to object–relational impedance mismatch, a mismatch occurs between the declarative SQL language and the procedural languages in which SQL is typically embedded.
